The subfamily Darninae , and specifically the tribe Darnini , is an understudied, poorly understood group. The tribe includes more than 86 species classified in 18 genera (
;
;
;
) distributed in America, from the southwest and southeast United States to northern Argentina . The monophyly of the tribe is supported by the presence of cucullate setae or short, strongly sclerotized studs on the ventral side of the femora (
;
; and see discussion). Subsocial behavior or ant-attendance has not been found among the Darnini . Adults and nymphs are usually found as solitary individuals (
; Kenji Nishida (pers. comm.) (LGM and SHM field observations).

